(10, 'Hariyana', 'New Delhi', 'image/destinations/new-delhi1807944517.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 1, 6, 'Indira Gandhi International Airport', 'New Delhi railway station', 'New Delhi is the capital of India and one of Delhi city\'s 11 districts. Although colloquially Delhi and New Delhi are used interchangeably to refer to the National Capital Territory of Delhi', NULL, '<h2><strong>Qutb Minar</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.tridindia.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/facts-about-Qutub-Minar.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Qutub Minar, also spelled as Qutab Minar, or Qutb Minar, is a minaret that forms a part of the Qutab complex, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in the Mehrauli area of Delhi</p>', '<h2><strong>Hotel Forest Green</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.content.tuigroup.com/adamtui/2016_9/22_16/a2b1cf6a-fc3c-4a25-aebc-a68901083087/TUR_HIS_3506WebOriginalCompressed.jpg?i10c=img.resize(width:1080);img.crop(width:1080%2Cheight:608)\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Book&nbsp;<em>Hotel Forest Green</em>&nbsp;in New Delhi at discounted rates. Read 9 hotel guest reviews of&nbsp;<em>Hotel Forest Green</em>&nbsp;and book today!</p>', '<h2><strong>Ashok Country Resort</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ui.cltpstatic.com/places/hotels/4120/41201/images/_DSC7404_w.jpg\" style=\"height:469px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Ashok Country Resort</em>&nbsp;is a family run Eco-friendly Boutique Hotel, near the Delhi International Airport situated only 4 Km. from Indira Gandhi International Airport and about 16 Km. from the Delhi commercial centre of Connaught Place, with the advent of a now business hub&nbsp; only 8 Km</p>', '<h2><strong>India Gate</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://static.dnaindia.com/sites/default/files/styles/full/public/2017/04/22/568212-india-gate1.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<em>India Gate</em>&nbsp;is a war memorial located astride the Rajpath, on the eastern edge of the &quot;ceremonial axis&quot; of New Delhi, India, formerly called Kingsway.&nbsp;<em>India Gate</em>&nbsp;is a memorial to 70,000 soldiers of the British Indian Army who died in the period 1914&ndash;21 in the First World War, in France, Flanders, Mesopotamia, Persia.</p>', '<p><strong>By Road :</strong>Delhi is well connected by bus to cities like Jaipur, Agra, Alwar, Chandigarh, Amritsar, Shimla, Manali, Dharamsala, Dehradun and even Kathmandu among others. The main bus stands in Delhi are the Interstate Bus Terminals, located at Kashmiri Gate, Anand Vihar and Sarai Kale Khan. Apart from that there&rsquo;s Mandi House (near Barakhamba Road) which has regular air-conditioned bus services to hill stations in Himachal Pradesh, such as Shimla, Manali, Kasauli etc.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Bikaner House (near Pandara Road) bus station has regular air conditioned buses to destinations in Rajasthan, such as Jaipur, Udaipur and Jodhpur. The Majnu ka Tila bus stand (near the Vidhan Sabha Metro Station) has regular buses to Dharamsala. The Delhi Metro and local DTC buses and auto rickshaws conveniently connect these bus stands to the rest of the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Rail :</strong>Delhi is the headquarters of the Northern Railways and there are five major railway stations in Delhi, namely the The New Delhi Railway Station, Old Delhi Railway Station, Nizamuddin Railway Station, Anand Vihar Railway Terminal and Sarai Rohilla. The New Delhi Railway Station is one through which most trains arrive and depart from Delhi and is located in Paharganj, near Connaught Place. There is a pre-paid taxi booth outside the railway station and you can take a taxi from here to go further into the city.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Delhi Metro line 2 also connects the New Delhi Railway Station to other parts of the city and is a convenient way to get into the city. There are also DTC buses (green and red coloured buses) which can take you into the city at a reasonable price. Apart from that you can also take auto rickshaws to places like Connuaght Place and Old Delhi. Though autos are supposed to go by the fare metre, many times they refuse to do so and it is best to ask a local how much the rough cost to a destination should be to make sure you are not cheated. You can also hop into a cycle rickshaw if you&rsquo;re going to Connaught Place, though cycle richshaws are not allowed inside Connaught Place and you&rsquo;ll be dropped slightly away from your destination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Air :</strong>Delhi&rsquo;s airport is the Indira Gandhi International airport and is very well connected to cities across India and the world. There are regular flights to Delhi from Mumbai, Bangalore, Chennai, Hyderabad, Lucknow, Goa, Kolkata, Guwahati and international destinations as well. The airport is divided into two terminals, namely Terminal 1D and Terminal 3. Terminal 1 D is the domestic airport and is primarily used by low cost airlines such as Spice Jet, IndiGo and Go Air among others. Terminal 3 or T3 as it is commonly known, is the international terminal which is used by all international carriers operating to Delhi and full fare domestic airlines. A free shuttle service operates between both terminals every 20 minutes.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Indira Gandhi International Airport is 22 kilometers away from the city centre. There are regular DTC (Delhi Transport Service) buses which operate regularly from outside the airport towards the city and the ISBT bus stand and the New Delhi Railway Station. The Delhi Airport Metro Express runs from the New Delhi Railway Station to Dwarka, crossing the airport along the way. The metro train service runs every 20 minutes and is a quick and convenient way to get to the city. You can also hire a pre-paid taxi from government registered counters at the airport, which would take you 40-50 minutes to get to the city centre depending on traffic</p>', NULL, NULL, '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://cdn77.orangesmile.com/common/img_cities_original/new-delhi--2106102-1.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Delhi offers much to see and do all through the year. Here&#39;s a seasonal break-up so you can plan your trip accordingly:&nbsp;<strong>October to March:</strong>&nbsp;The start of autumn, which gradually leads to a crisp and pleasant winter, this is the best time to visit Delhi. Winters in the capital can get really cold, with the minimum temperature dropping down to 2 degrees Celsius in the month of January, but afternoons are mostly sunny and pleasant. Enjoy sightseeing, shopping or just ambling through the sun bathed streets of Delhi. Don&rsquo;t forget to carry your woolens along, as mornings and evenings can get particularly cold. October is also the time for one of Delhi&#39;s biggest festivities - Diwali. Visit Delhi during Diwali or Dussehra, and you will be welcomed by a beautifully decorated city bustling with activity. This is also the time when Delhi hosts a number of film, drama, music and literature festivals.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>April to June:</strong>&nbsp;This is the beginning of summer and when tourists generally tend to retreat. It&#39;s the perfect time to have Delhi all to yourself and take advantage of off season hotel prices. During summers the temperatures can go up to 45 degrees Celsius. End May and June are the hottest months. Make sure you carry light cotton clothes, sunscreen and sunglasses to beat the heat and enjoy the sights of the city.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>July to September:</strong>&nbsp;July marks the beginning of monsoon and this is when you can enjoy Delhi in its rain washed splendour. Monsoons in Delhi are when the city is at its most beautiful. This is also a great time to enjoy Delhi&rsquo;s lush green parks and gardens. Don&rsquo;t forget to carry an umbrella or a raincoat.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 'new-delhi', '2018-08-01 07:16:55', '2018-08-01 01:46:55'),
(11, 'Odisha', 'Puri', 'image/destinations/puri1693331910.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 2, 6, 'Talabania Helipad', 'Puri railway station', 'Puri is a city and a Municipality in the state of Odisha in eastern India. It is the district headquarters of Puri district and is situated on the Bay of Bengal, 60 kilometres south of the state capital of Bhubaneswar.', '<p>Puri is a city and a Municipality in the state of Odisha in eastern India. It is the district headquarters of Puri district and is situated on the Bay of Bengal, 60 kilometres south of the state capital of Bhubaneswar.</p>', '<h2><strong>Puri Beach</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://1913578542.rsc.cdn77.org/pictures/travel_guide/fairandfestival/page/puri-beach-festival-56.jpeg\" style=\"height:278px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Puri Beach is a beach in the city of Puri in the state of Odisha, India. It is on the shore of the Bay of Bengal. It is known for being a tourist attraction and a Hindu sacred place.</p>', '<h2><strong>Hotel Sakthi International</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://blessingsonthenet.com/img/uploads/hotels/aim_bn_1374819138.jpg\" style=\"height:379px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Shakti International</em>&nbsp;is the only ISO 9001:2008 certified&nbsp;<em>Hotels</em>&nbsp;in Puri,Odisha. We are one of the premier 3 star&nbsp;<em>hotels</em>&nbsp;in Puri. Find details about Puri&nbsp;<em>Hotels</em>,Budget&nbsp;<em>Hotels</em>&nbsp;in Puri near Beach and Star<em>Hotels</em>&nbsp;in Puri Odisha from www.shaktiinternational.in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<h2><strong>Hotel Holiday Resort</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://t-ec.bstatic.com/images/hotel/max1024x768/320/32076588.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Puri&nbsp;<em>Holiday Resort</em>&nbsp;is one of the premium&nbsp;<em>Hotels</em>&nbsp;in Puri, Temple town, which offers most relaxing stay for travellers, special discount and offers Book Now!</p>', '<h2><strong>Jaganath Temple Puri</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://image3.mouthshut.com/images/imagesp/925769994s.jpg\" style=\"height:533px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Shree&nbsp;<em>Jagannath Temple</em>&nbsp; of&nbsp;<em>Puri</em>&nbsp;is an important Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Jagannath, a form of lord Vishnu, located on the eastern coast of India, at&nbsp;<em>Puri</em>&nbsp;in the state of Odisha. The temple is an important pilgrimage destination and one of the four great &#39;Char Dham&#39; pilgrimage sites, found&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><strong>By Road :</strong>The bus stand near the Gundicha Temple provides connections to Bhubaneswar and Cuttack, service every 10-15 minutes. Minibuses to Konark leave every 20-30 minutes and also from Jatiababa Chhak. There are direct buses for Kolkata and Visakhapatnam.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Rail :</strong>Puri is a terminus on the East Coast Railway having direct express and super fast train links with New Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Okha, Ahmedabad, Tirupati etc. Some important trains are Kolkata (Howrah) Puri Howrah Express, Jagannath Express; New Delhi; Purushottam Express. Khurda Road Station, 44 km, from Puri is convenient rail head for train to Chennai and Western India.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Air :</strong>&nbsp;The nearest airport is Bhubaneswar, 60 km.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'puri', '2018-07-16 07:21:59', '2018-07-16 01:51:59'),
(12, 'West Bengal', 'Darjeeling', 'image/destinations/darjeeling1806584913.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 2, 12, 'Bagdogra Airport', 'Darjeeling railway station', 'Darjeeling is a town in India\'s West Bengal state, in the Himalayan foothills. Once a summer resort for the British Raj elite, it remains the terminus of the narrow-gauge Darjeeling Himalayan Railway, or “Toy Train,” completed in 1881. It\'s famed for the distinctive black tea grown on plantations that dot its surrounding slopes. Its backdrop is Mt. Kanchenjunga, among the world’s highest peaks.', NULL, '<h2><strong>Tiger Hill&nbsp;Darjeeling</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://image3.mouthshut.com/images/Restaurant/Photo/-96563_10973.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Tiger Hill</em>&nbsp;(2,590 m) is located in&nbsp;<em>Darjeeling</em>, in the Indian State of West Bengal, and is the summit of Ghoom, the highest railway station in the&nbsp;<em>Darjeeling</em>&nbsp;Himalayan Railway &ndash; a UNESCO World Heritage Site. It has a panoramic view of Mount Everest and Mount Kangchenjunga together. It is 11 km from the town of&nbsp;<em>Darjeeling</em></p>', '<h2><strong>Summit Grace Hotel &amp; Spa</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://content3.jdmagicbox.com/comp/darjeeling/p9/9999px354.x354.170112235326.j6p9/catalogue/summit-grace-hotel-spa-darjeeling-hotels-f0z9b.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Summit Grace Hotel &amp; Spa</em>, a 4 star resort, is a stone&#39;s throw from the famous Darjeeling Peace Pagoda. Romantic architecture, with subtle Italian influences, makes the property impressive. With 9 Deluxe Rooms and 7 Suites, the exclusive property radiates warmth and elegance.</p>', '<h2><strong>Sterling Darjeeling - Resorts and Hotels</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://s-ec.bstatic.com/images/hotel/max1024x768/544/54491292.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Modern comfort at the&nbsp;<em>Sterling Darjeeling resort</em>&nbsp;is steeped in the tranquility of the surrounding mountains enhancing the charm of this lovely town, Colonial buildings, Gothic churches, Buddhist monasteries, all make for a beautiful holiday.</p>', '<h2><strong>Mirik</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://northbengaltourism.com/images/darjeeling/mirik_1024.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mirik is a picturesque tourist spot nestled in the serene hills of Darjeeling district in West Bengal, India. It is the headquarters of Mirik subdivision. The name Mirik comes from the Lepcha words Mir-Yok meaning &quot;place burnt by fire&quot;</p>', '<p><strong>By Road :</strong>There are regular buses including Rocket and Volvo services between Kolkata (Calcutta) and Siliguri Main Bus Terminal (known as Tenzing Norgay Bus Terminus located on Hill Cart Road). From Siliguri main bus terminal area, you will get buses, shared Jeeps and private taxis for Darjeeling. Distance between Siliguri and Darjeeling is 80kms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Rail :</strong>Take a train up to NJP (New Jalpaiguri). Darjeeling is only 88kms from here. You will get ample taxis and shared jeeps from NJP to reach Darjeeling in about 3 hours. Few long distance trains pass through Siliguri as well. You will also get plenty of shared jeeps, taxis and buses at Siliguri (takes about 2.5 hours to Darjeeling). You can even take a toy train ride from either NJP or Siliguri through scenic mountain route that takes about 7 hours to reach Darjeeling. The toy train track runs parallel and next to the Hill Cart Road for most part. Check&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.darjeeling-tourism.com/darj_000089.htm\">Toy Train Service</a>&nbsp;for schedule and running status.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Air :</strong>Fly down to the nearest airport Bagdogra which is 94 kms from Darjeeling town and take a private taxi. Shared taxis and buses are not available here. It takes little over 3 hours to reach Darjeeling from Bagdogra airport.&nbsp;</p>', '<h2><strong>Rink Mall</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://c8.alamy.com/comp/DW8EM7/dubai-mall-ice-rink-with-people-ice-skating-dubai-uae-united-arab-DW8EM7.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For travelers missing out on city life in Darjeeling,&nbsp;<em>Rink Mall</em>&nbsp;is a go-to destination for a &ldquo;mall experience&rdquo; amidst the beautiful surroundings. This place, located at the entrance of Mall road, attracts a lot of tourists. Tired travelers can take delight by relaxing in the massage chairs near the entrance. If you are looking at gorging&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.indiamarks.com/wp-content/uploads/best_time_to_visit_Darjeeling.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While summer months from April to June are the ideal time to travel to Darjeeling, some travellers including couples also prefer to visit the beautiful town during winter months from October to December. However, it would be great to look at the monthly breakup of Darjeeling&rsquo;s climatic conditions so that you can plan when to go:&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOctober to March: October is when the monsoon season ends and a slight chill is observed in the weather. Winter season begins in full swing and it is during the months of mid-November to January, when the average temperature ranges between 7 and 5 degree Celsius. Snowfall is rarely seen in Darjeeling. But sometimes, the temperature can drop down to -2 degree Celsius, so make sure you pack some woollens.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nApril to June: These months constitute the summer season in Darjeeling which is quite pleasant and not harsh. The maximum temperature is around 25 degree Celsius. Bright sunlight packed with windy air in the evenings make for a great vacation in Darjeeling amidst the picturesque surroundings. This time is also good for sightseeing and other tourist activities. :&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJuly to September: Starting July till August, heavy rainfall is observed in Darjeeling. It might not be the best time to visit the place during the monsoons as you can come across some roadblocks. However, if you love the rains, don&rsquo;t miss the lush-green environ drenched in rain water which calls for great photographic shots as well. That said, September is a good time to visit the place as there&rsquo;s less rainfall and the greenery remains intact.</p>', NULL, 'darjeeling', '2018-07-04 12:49:00', '2018-07-04 07:19:00'),
(13, 'Kerala', 'Kerala', 'image/destinations/kerala1267995542.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 2, 10, 'Cochin International Airport (25 km)', 'North Railway Station , Cochin', 'Well known as God’s Own Country, one of the best south Indian state is blessed with rivers, greenery, natural diversity, fertile land, and a\r\nrich history and unique culture to the region. Kerala is the land to a diverse atmosphere, culturally and topographically. From the coastal\r\ntowns, the Western Ghats and hill stations, to its elaborate, and its well known famous backwaters, palm tree, and lakes, Kerala has a\r\nlot to offer to the wanderlust soul.', '<p>The Western Ghats, bordering the eastern boundary of the State, form an almost continuous mountain wall, except near Palakkad where there is a natural mountain pass known as the Palakkad Gap. The average elevation of the Ghats is about 1500 meters above sea level, occasionally soaring to peaks of 2000 to 2500 meters. From the Ghats, the land slopes to the west on to the plains, into an unbroken coastline.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe strip of hills and valleys on the eastern edge, close to the Ghats, comprises steep mountains and deep valleys, covered with dense forests. Almost all the rivers of the State originate here. There are 44 rivers in the state, of which 41 originate from the Western Ghats and flow towards west into the Arabian Sea. Only three tributaries of the river Cauvery originate in Kerala and flow east into the neighbouring States. These rivers and streams flowing down from the Western Ghats into the backwaters in the coastal area or directly into the Arabian Sea. As the Western Ghats are nowhere more than 120 km from the sea, all these rivers are comparatively short.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the Midland Plains of central Kerala, the hills are not very steep and the valleys are wide. The valleys have been developed as paddy fields and the elevated lands and hill slopes are converted into estates of rubber, fruit trees and other cash crops like pepper, areca nut and tapioca.&nbsp; Tea and&nbsp; coffee estates have cropped up in the high ranges during the last two centuries.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Coastal belt is comparatively plain. Extensive paddy fields, thick groves of coconut trees and picturesque backwaters, interconnected with canals and rivers are the features of this region. No wonder, Alappuzha, an old sea port town of this region is known as the&nbsp; &#39;Venice of the East&#39;. In the southern and northern parts of the State the coastal belt also has some small hillocks.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Backwaters &amp; Rivers</strong><br />\r\nThe backwaters are a peculiar feature of the State. Canals link the lakes and backwaters to facilitate an uninterrupted inland water navigation system from Thiruvananthapuram to Vadakara, a distance of 450 km. The Vembanad lake stretching from Alappuzha to Kochi is the biggest water body in the State and is over 200 sq.km in area. Kuttanad in Alappuzha district alone has more than 20 per cent of India&#39;s total length of waterways.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe important rivers from north to south are; Valapattanam river (110 km), Chaliar (69 km), Kadalundipuzha (130 km), Bharathapuzha (209 km), Chalakudy river (130 km), Periyar (244 km), Pamba (176 km), Achancoil (128 km) and Kalladayar (121 km). Other than these, there are about 35 small rivers and rivulets flowing down from the Western Ghats. Most of these rivers are navigable up to the midland region, in country crafts.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://holidaysgenius.com/media/uploads/2015/12/Kumbalangi-Integrated-Tourism-Village.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kerala has a unique culture with the rich heritage. You will find the rural areas still pursuing on to their age-old customs, and at the same time the town areas are hitting up with other modern metro cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Cultural Destinations: </strong> Kerala, with its archaic Indian history and unique architectural literary, with cultural heritage, has a lot to offer to culture lovers. Explore the cultural heritage of a land which was governed by some of the great legendary dynasties that reigned in the region. Kerala also a land of temples, mosque, and churches. Those not only emphasize the beauty of architecture but also giving a great positive impact on believers hearts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://irisholidays.com/keralatourism/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/shakthan-thampuran-palace-thrissur.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Palaces and Forts:</strong> Visit the stunning Mattancherry Palace and synagogue, Krishnapuram Palace the Bekal Fort, Kilimanur Palace and Fort Immanuel and many more be stunned by Keralas historical heritage and architectural symphony.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://images.anchoice.cz/110/609777/original/609777-6.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Sight-Seeing:</strong> With multitudes of backwaters with exotic houseboats and rivers, Kerala is filled with chances to spend time in the bed of nature. Some must visit places are Munnar and its broad tea estates, Wayanad and its vast tea and coffee estates, the Alappuzha and Kollam backwaters and houseboats, Kannur beaches, parambikulam wildlife Sanctuary Kumarakom Bird Sanctuary, Kovalam beaches,&nbsp;athirapali waterfalls and its forests, the list goes on.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.keralatravelplanner.in/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/how-to_reach-kerala.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kerala has well-established Road networks, Rail and Air routes that you can take to reach the entire state. All the major destinations are interconnected with perfect roadways. The remarkable thing is, the state also has some water routes available too!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;By Air</strong>: The major International Airports in Kerala are located in Kochi, Calicut, and Trivandrum. There are buses to different parts&nbsp;of the state from each of these airports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; By Rail:</strong> Kerala is well connected by railways, except for the Ghats section and hilly terrain. Southern Railways has its magic and the vertically spanned state of Kerala is thoroughly tracery with railway lines ensuring secure inter-state connectivity. Another attraction is the tickets aren&#39;t too expensive for a budget traveler.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; By Road:</strong>&nbsp;Kerala has best and well-maintained roads. The state has 11 National highways and about 70 state highways, roads are well connected with the terrain. The best advantage is the natural beauty that runs along with the roadways. There are many bus services from different states to Kerala and within the state, there is a good network of state government buses and private buses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://cdn.fcglcdn.com/brainbees/images/Store/183_04.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;You have innumerable verities for purchase to fill your bags .The best will be able to buy most spices, tea, and coffee at any market in Kerala but when it comes to being organic and really fragrant when its from beautiful hill stations., the tea and coffee have a spectacularly strong flavor because of the fertile land and weathercondition The best places to buy them are at Munnar and Wayanad.&nbsp; Other legendary things are the handicraft items like.,aramula kannadi&nbsp;,small boat statue, coir products, elephant figures statues, traditional lamp kasavu sari&hellip;etc.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.munroeislandlakeresort.in/images/food/food-8.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;All the nook and corners of Kerala is marked with good restaurants with local and versatile delicacies to try.,The Tapioca preparations and the different fish curries and fries that are best coastal dishes. At breakfast, you should try the edly with chutney, appam and will get the number of curry options for the combo, or puttu, also called bamboo cake You must also try out the different. Of course, you cannot miss all the tender coconut if there is one cure for the Kerala heat, it&rsquo;s the best magnificent drink. Also, if you&#39;re in northern parts like Calicut or Kannur, try some of the best Malabar style Biryani with lemon sulaimani, the mind-blowing combination of Malabar biriyani</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://dimensionemedica.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/kerala.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different parts of Kerala can experience different weather conditions because of its diverse terrain, In the summers it can get bit hot and humid climate, especially along the coastal side, this, however, would be a great time to visit the hill stations of Ponmudi, Munnar, Wayanad, etc which provide pretty cool atmosphere.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Kerala is blessed with romantic rain during the monsoon season, that time soil tends to get a little too wet but this is not much of a hindrance for your movement, as Kerala in the rains is genuinely beautiful especially in the banks of backwaters and worth witnessing. Winter is the best time to explore Kerala and the temperatures and weather conditions are just perfect for a lovely holiday.</p>', '<p>Youve known about all the wonderful sights, places, sounds, and foods of this delicious coastal land. But before you embark on your tripthere, heres a quick overview of the most delightful things to enjoy in Gods Own Country.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>1. Watch a Kalaripayattu</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.keralatourism.org/images/artforms/large/kalaripayattu20131111114353_27_1.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This is one of Kerala&#39;s ancient legendary martial art form Kalaripayattu regarded as one of the veterans and most scientific of its kind in the world. It focusing on the best perfecting the coordination between the body, mind and the instrument. Actions like jumping, running and somersaulting are tough tricks, followed by the practice in the use of combat weapons such as swords, daggers, spears, maces, etc. An extra vagant treat of eyes!</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>2. Enjoy a Kathakali Performance</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.kathakalicentre.com/uploads/pics/baner3.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The art form which entered in Guinness record for its extraordinary combination of makeups and elaborate costumes. Kathakali is a highly complicated and stylish classical Keralan play- in-dance form, intricate gesturing and with hypnotic percussions. It originated during the&nbsp;17th century, it has developed over the years with improvisations in the looks of characters, refining of gestures and added themes. Most of the story is related to Hindu Purana epics and stories. The story of Nala charitham and the keechakavadham are the famous plays on the list.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>3. Stay a night in Homestay.</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://d27k8xmh3cuzik.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Cover4.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Live a day in any of the ultra-hospitable local families, enjoy their food, mingle with them and catch their culture and lifestyle. The most authentic way to experience the state of Kerala! you will get the facilities in all major destinations like Wayanad, Munnar, Alappuzha etc</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>4. Enjoy an Elephant Ride</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://d1jgrpnx5qsq8g.cloudfront.net/images/content/1280x720/elephant-riding.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Feel the big !! This is one of the best action to do in Kerala - just so that you don&#39;t ever regret that you came to our land and didn&#39;t feel the thrill of an elephant ride first hand! the activity is very safe and entirely thrilling with fun. It&#39;s even possible to get a short wildlife safari on an elephant back!</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>5. Experience Nilgiri tahr and Neelakuriji</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://wandernow.in/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Nilgiri-Tahr-_-Neelakurinji.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Both are the enchanting beauty of Munnar, the neelakuriji (strobilanthes kunthiana) floriated on the time span of 12 years, it&rsquo;s worth full to see that entire area at that time, the Nilgiri tahr can see very close to our eyes without any nets, with the marvelous climate of Munnar</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>6. Theyyam Performance</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4048/4542576897_ace222e7d9_b.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Theyyam is a form of God, form of worship where the man dons the elaborate makeup with the costume of a fierce God, like a great warrior and attempts to commune with the Gods through ritualistic dancing. The performance of Theyyam is supposed to make life remove all obstacles and for a healthy and prosperous life, in southern states its known as mudiyet. Its similar to theyam but the story and ritualistic performance is bit different.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>7. Take a Boat-ride in the Periyar River</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.keralaleisureholidays.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/thekkady-boating-1.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Enjoying the greenery is the best thing of Kerala With its frosted water its going like like a silver belt through the forest and wondrous&nbsp;views of the jungles, elephants on either side, an early morning ride down the Periyar River, particularly in winter, it&#39;s feeling like heaven., it is also ranked as one of the Top 10 wildlife safaris in India and the Sunrises over the river are just breathtaking!</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>8. Pamper yourself with an Ayurveda Massage</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://healthxtourism.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Ayurvedic-Massage-in-Dubai.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ayurveda Massage is to rejuvenate your body and mind, its a combination of ancient science and art. It is recommended for the relaxation of body and mind as well as for amply stimulation of nerves and muscles. Mineral based oil and Warm plant are massaged into the muscles and allowed to seep in overtime using hot towel wraps. It helps to reduce the number of toxins present in the skin, as well as mobilize toxins within the joints, muscles, and organs. But you have to choose the right center for its.. our client reviews and our team will help with the best one because of its mater of health.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>8. Sail down the Alleppey Backwaters at Sunset</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://lonelyindia.files.wordpress.com/2015/03/mg_6877.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Alleppey..the Venice of the east is renowned for its pristine seashore and picture-perfect coconut palm fringed. But the real hi-lights are the backwaters that big snake around this village towns. Hire a houseboat and kick back with some fresh coconut toddy or tender coconut and watch the sun take a blazing red with gold curtain call for the day. And also enjoy the tasty karimeen (black moly) with rice and kappa.. in the mid of backwaters, you will get wow moment.</p>', 'kerala', '2018-10-10 11:16:47', '2018-10-10 15:16:47'),
(14, 'Kerala', 'Kovalam', 'image/destinations/kovalam1800107805.jpeg', 'May', 'October', 2, 5, 'Kovalam Airport', 'Kovalam Railway Station', 'Some of the must see in Kerala include the backwaters at Alleppey and Kumarakom; beaches like Kovalam and Marai; hill stations like Munnar and Wayand; historic places like Bekal and Fort Kochi; wildlife destinations like Periyar and Chinnar and religious places like Sree Padmanabhswamy Temple, St. Francis Church, mosque like Cherai Juma Masjid, and Jewish Synagogue like Paradesi.', '<p>Enjoy scrumptious German Breakfast at German Bakery. The watersports enthusiasts can indulge in surfing activity at Kovalam Surf Club and snorkeling at Eve&#39;s beach. Those feeling lazy can rejuvenate themselves with various Ayurveda massages, designed to soothe both the body and soul. Spending a day in serenity at Hawa Beach also one of the best things to do in Kovalam. Apart from it one can pay a visit to Kovalam villages,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>where one can see and purchase some unique artifacts, inlay work, textile block printing, stone cutting, etc. It is an ideal place to pick up ethnic curios and other articles. Other than this, watch cultural and heritage art forms at centres in Kovalam. Here ceremonies are organized bring prosperity and happiness. Yet another good vacation experience to get in Kovalam is early morning Catamaran sailing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shopping in Kovalam is something tourists can just afford to miss. Handicrafts, seashells, junk jewelry, and garments are available everywhere at affordable prices. People can visit the Varkala Beach near Kovalam which is the heaven for shopaholics. Whether it&#39;s puppet from Rajasthan or jewelry from Bhutan, each and everything tourists can purchase from beaches of Kovalam.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'kovalam', '2018-06-25 01:31:42', '2018-06-25 01:31:42'),
(15, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Ooty', 'image/destinations/ooty-munnar-kodaikanal-tour1089465269.jpeg', 'March', 'June', 1, 5, 'Coimbatore', 'Udhagamandalam railway station', 'Located in the Western Ghats at a height of 7,500ft, Oooty/ Udhagamandalam is the headquarters of the Nilgiri district. Ooty was the former summer retreat of the British. John Sullivan, the collector of Coimbatore who founded the first European settlement here, stumbled across Ooty\'s idyllic scenery in 19th century during one of his nomadic searches for rare flowers. The name Ooty or Ootacamund derives its name from the local Toda word Udhamandalam meaning village of huts.  The Tamil \'Whotai\'  a species of dwarf bamboo that grows in the forests, \'kai\' meaning a fruit or green stuff in the middle and the Toda \'mund\' meaning a village clapped at the end. Ooty, however, got its name during the British rule, by calling \'WOTYKAMUND\' in the Madras gazette.', '<p>Ooty has become more of a &#39;honeymooner&nbsp;paradise&#39; and a de-facto filming location. Apart from coffee and tea plantations, trees like conifers, pine and wattle dot the hillside of Oooty and its environs. While visiting you will also come across many eucalyptus trenches. The fresh smell of eucalyptus trees in a trendy and clement breeze will make you psychedelic for sure. The funnel-shaped blossoms covering the hills in floral profusion and the lavender-blue flowers spread over the mountains will pack you with memories for a lifetime.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ooty has many places to see. The idyllic valley views, tranquil forest ranges, beautiful flora and fauna with bustling music of the wildlife.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Botanical Garden</strong><br />\r\nBuilt in 1847, by an English gardener Marquis of Tweeddale, this quite, the beautiful, well-maintained garden covers an area of 22 acres.&nbsp; It has 2000 different species of trees, fashioned beds laid out&nbsp;in an Italian style, beautiful flowers including orchids, a fossil tree trunk of 20 million years, a small artificial pond, alpines, and medicinal plants among beautiful lawns and glass houses. The bushes are cut into the shapes of animals and birds.&nbsp;<br />\r\nAn annual flower show is held here in third week May every year. This show is one of the main attraction of Ooty. The rose garden 750m from Charing Cross contains over 1,500 varieties of roses. It is open from 0800 to 1800. The best time is from September to October and from April to May of the year. Timing - 8 A.M&nbsp; -6 A.M. Entrance fee: Rs. 5 per head for adults, Children- Rs.2<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Ooty Lake</strong><br />\r\nAn artificial lake constructed between 1823 and 1825 by Mr.John Sullivan, as an irrigation tank. The 2.5km long lake covers an area of more that 25hectre with the famous narrow-gauge toy railway line running along one bank; rowing boats are available for hire. You can also go for horse-back riding around the lake. This is one of the most popular tourist spots. Pony rides for children is a major attraction. The mini-train for children is still another attraction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Doddabeta&nbsp; Peak&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAbout 10km East of the Railway Station, off the Kotagiri Rd 2623 meters the highest peak This is a great place to enjoy the spectacular view of&nbsp;the mountainous valleys and peaks. The place is very serene. This place has a nice view tower wherein you can use high-power TTDC telescope to view surrounding places.&nbsp; On a bright day, one can have a bird&#39;s eye view of the plains of Coimbatore and&nbsp; Mysore, the plateau&nbsp;towns Ooty and Coonoor and the barracks at Wellington can also be seen at a distance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Pykara&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSituated at a distance of 19 km. from Ooty,&nbsp; the river has a dam and a power plant. The great charm of the place is its perfect serenity, sparkling atmosphere, and enchanting surroundings. The falls, about 6km from the bridge on the main road, is best in July. There is a Forest Rest House and a boat House with Restaurant is at Pykara. .Boats are available for hire in Pykara dam.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stone House</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis house was built by John Sullivan. It was occupied by the Principal of the Govt. Art College. The tribals called it as Kal Bangla (stone bungalow).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>St.Stephens Church</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;It is the first church built in Ooty,1820.&nbsp;It is said that the wood for this church was brought from Tipu Sultan&#39;s Lal Bagh Palace in Srirangapatnam after his final defeat. These wood had to be hauled up by the elephants from the plains.&nbsp;It has a clock tower, nine tubular bells, and a gallery</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Black Thunder</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAsia&#39;s No. 1 Water Theme Park - Black Thunder, is set at the foothills of the gigantic Nilgris and 50 km from Ooty. It is a thrilling and adventures water theme park at Mettupalayam. The water theme park is spread over 65 acres of land with green hills as a backdrop and full of coconut and arecanut trees is a pleasant atmosphere. This park has adventurous water games and land games.</p>', NULL, '<h2><strong>Accord High Land</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Overlooking the beautiful Nilgiris Mountains, the hotel stands tall with all elegance and style. A contemporary structure with a traditional feel, Highland Hotel Ooty is located at one of the most picturesque location in Ooty, at 2240 meters above sea level in the Nilgiris Hills of southern India.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSituated amidst the exquisite Blue Mountains, popularly known as Nilgiris, Highland Hotel Ooty is the highest hotel in Southern India and an inspiring destination for leisure, Honeymooners &amp; corporate travelers. The hotel is situated on a 10 acre landscaped hill slope, overlooking the beautiful valley.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHighland Hotel Ooty being the premier leisure hotel in Ooty has 49 beautifully well-appointed rooms and 4 suites. For meetings &amp; parties, the hotel offers three banquet halls on a dedicated floor with a capacity to accommodate up to 200 guests. The room and suite interiors are aesthetically done with classic furnishings. Highland Hotel Ooty Offers a substantial array of cuisines with multi cuisine menu including Oriental, Continental and Indian cuisines.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe second phase of property development will include adding of 40 individual cottages with temperature controlled private pools, state of the art spa meeting international standards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ooty-munnar-kodaikanal-tour', '2019-06-13 06:32:44', '2019-06-13 10:32:44'),
(16, 'Rajasthan', 'Jaipur', 'image/destinations/jaipur1652182765.jpeg', 'October', 'March', 2, 6, 'Jaipur International Airport', 'Jaipur Railway Station', 'Ruling from the magnificent Amber Fort which they built, the might of the Kucchwahas encompassed the kingdoms of Mewar (Udaipur) and Marwar (Jodhpur). After Jai Singh came to power, there was moment of disquiet when he supported Aurangzeb’s son Azam Shah’s bid to the throne. Azam Shah lost the battle of succession to his brother Bahadur Shah, who demanded Jai Singh’s removal and the installation of Vijay Singh to the throne of Jaipur. Jai Singh, not one to take setbacks lying down, formed a formidable front against the Mughals by aligning himself with other Rajput states and reinstated himself.\r\n\r\nAfter the dust had settled, peace reigned and the kingdom prospered and its borders expanded. Jai Singh built the city around the Amber fort to serve as his capital, and the city was named Jaipur, after himself. Much of the credit for Jaipur goes to Vidhyadhar Bhattacharya, the chief architect from Bengal who, with Jai Singh’s approval, founded the city on strong scientific principles, laid out according to the Shilpa Shastra, the ancient architectural manual. It remains one of India’s best planned cities.However, expansion meant that the limited sources of water proved inadequate for the city.\r\n\r\nAfter Jai Singh’s death in 1744, his sons squabbled for power and without a monarch, the kingdom became open to invasion and neighboring Rajput states and the Marathas usurped large areas of kingdom. The core, however, remained part of the kingdom, which lasted during British times. As with the Mughals, Jaipur maintained good relations with the British and during the war of independence in 1857 remained loyal to the Raj. Yet, the British gradually began to undermine the independence of the state and exercised greater control over the administration.\r\n\r\nIn 1876, Maharaja Ram Singh painted the entire city pink, traditionally a colour associated with hospitality, to welcome the Prince of Wales (later King Edward VII) to the city. The tradition has been maintained and today all residents in the old city are compelled by law to preserve the pink color. Jaipur got the sobriquet of pink city.', '<p>Jaipur is a major tourist destination in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India\">India</a>&nbsp;forming a part of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_Triangle_(India)\">Golden Triangle</a>. In the 2008 Conde Nast Traveller Readers Choice Survey, Jaipur was ranked the 7th best place to visit in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia\">Asia</a>.According to TripAdvisor&#39;s 2015 Traveller&#39;s Choice Awards for Destination, Jaipur ranked 1st among the Indian destinations for the year.The Presidential Suite at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Raj_Palace\">Raj Palace Hotel</a>, billed at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_dollar\">US</a>&nbsp;45,000&nbsp;per night, was listed in second place on CNN&#39;s&nbsp;<em>World&#39;s 15 most expensive hotel suites</em>&nbsp;in 2012</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'jaipur', '2018-06-25 04:40:40', '2018-06-25 04:40:40');
