(27, 'Kerala', 'Alappuzha', 'image/destinations/alappuzha1085348348.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 2, 7, 'Cochin International Airport (52 km)', 'Alappuzha (4 km)', 'Alappuzha or Alleppey, is beautiful backwater destination in Kerala, more fondly known as the Venice of the East, is familiar for the rustic backwaters and its unforgettable houseboat cruises. Besides being the oldest planned city in the region, This beach town has been quite central to the history of the region.\r\nAlappuzha, the town has been home to the Punnapra-Valayar uprising and the revolt against the Feudal raj. Alleppey was well rated the cleanest town in India by the Center for Science and Environment in 2016. Tourism in Alleppey is just as clean and splendid as the city. The city gained importance during the Chera rule and to an extent, the Cheras set the base for the modern-day Alleppey. Christianity has held a strong foothold in the area since long with the port town being highly influenced by the Portuguese, Dutch and British invasions. Alappuzha, the town has been home to the Punnapra-Valayar uprising and the revolt against the Feudal raj. Alleppey was well rated the cleanest town in India by the Center for Science and Environment in 2016. Tourism in Alleppey is just as clean and splendid as the city. The city gained importance during the Chera rule and to an extent, the Cheras set the base for the modern-day Alleppey. Christianity has held a strong foot hold in the area since long with the port town being highly influenced by the Portuguese, Dutch and British invasions.', NULL, '<p>Standing strong with some of the most renowned tourist locations in the world for houseboats is the land of Alleppey in the southernmost Indian state of Kerala&nbsp;The backwaters of Alleppey have gained prominence throughout this century and is only getting more popular by the day, helped immensely by the sweet, cool weather in Alleppey, almost all year round. If you&#39;ve been wondering about the best time to visit Alleppey, read on to make a well-informed choice</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://img.theculturetrip.com/1024x/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/alleppey-abhisheka-kumar-wikicommons.jpg\" style=\"height:534px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Houseboat cruising</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Allepey is famous for its azure blue backwaters and its charming houseboats. Enchanting the breathtaking landscapes of God&#39;s Own Country while you sail peaceful on a wonderful houseboat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b9/AC_Road_SH-11.JPG\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alappuzha tourist spot in Kerala, the city is well connected by roads, rail, and air. The closest airport is located 78 km away at Cochin while the railway station is just 4 km from the city center. State-run, as well as private buses, connect Alleppey to major cities and towns in Kerala and neighboring states. State highways SH66, SH40, and SH11 connect Alleppey to other places. A drive down these roads is quite picturesque and memorable. Meanwhile, within Alleppey, the ideal mode of transport for travelers is the well maintained public bus service. One may even choose to opt for autos or ferries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>By&nbsp;Air: </strong>The closest airport to Alleppey is the Cochin International Airport located 78 km away.&nbsp;All major domestic carriers fly to Cochin. Some international carriers that connect to Cochin are Singapore Airlines, Jet Airways, Qatar Airways, Gulf Air and Etihad Airways.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>By Rail</strong>: The Alleppey Railway Station is 4 km from the city center. Major metropolitan cities like Bengaluru, Chennai, Hyderabad, Mumbai, and Kolkata&nbsp;are connected to Alleppey by the Indian railways. Some of the trains that operate to Alleppey daily are Bangalore City Kochuveli Express, Alleppey Dhanbad Express, Alleppey Express, Mangalore&nbsp;Central Maveli Express, Jan Shatabdi, Tatanagar Alleppey Express and Netravati Express. You could take a taxi, bus or auto-rickshaw to the main city.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>By&nbsp;Road:</strong> Alleppey has the best and well-maintained roads. Alleppey or Alappuzha is well connected by State Highways SH66, SH40 and SH11. The best merit is the natural beauty that runs along with the best roadways. There are a lot of bus services from different district of Kerala, there is a good network of state government buses and private buses.</li>\r\n</ul>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.greengroupexports.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/coir-products-green-group-exports.png\" style=\"height:447px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alapuzha is well known for its coir industry, so carpets and wares made of coir would be on your top and best shopping list. If you&#39;re looking to buy jewelry, head out to Gold, Silver &amp; Diamond Street, which stocks up on finely crafted jewelry. Alleppey is also famous for its spices, especially pepper, areca nut, and cardamom and numerous small shops are selling the finest quality spices and fresh coconut oil. Also visit the Mullackal Shopping spot, which has stores selling lime, jasmine, and sandalwood, along with carving knives, combs, games, toys, clothes, incense, wood carvings, and heavy metal utensils. There are also numerous shops selling muslin, bronze and copper wares. Some of Kerala&#39;s best brands of umbrellas can be found here, so head to Popy&#39;s and St George. Seemati Store also houses a fine collection of gold-bordered saris at affordable rates.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://img.manoramaonline.com/content/dam/mm/en/travel/getting-about-kerala/alappuzha/images/2019/5/7/houseboat-trip-and-food.jpg\" style=\"height:417px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The favorite cuisine of people in Alappuzha includes Rice, spicy curry with a local specialty of steamed rice cake served with coconut topping. The town has something or the else to serve to both vegetarians and non-vegetarians. To gorge on typical South Indian delicacies such as Dosa, Sambar, Vada, there is no dearth of restaurants as well as small eating joints. Seafood is the main highlight of the cuisine of Alappuzha. kari&not;meen Pollichathu, pearl spot fish baked over coals, Karimeen curry and viral fry are some of the main seafood dishes of Alleppey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are several restaurants and eating joints to cater to the food needs of tourists, according to their liking and budget. If you wish to eat Chinese, Indian or any other world cuisine, there are options for you too. Arun hotel, Annapoorna Restaurant, hotel Raja are some of such names.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;For are vegetarians, you can visit Hot Kitchen, located on Mullackal road and Sree Durga Bhavan Udipi Hotel on The Cullan road. Without thinking much, you can place an order for mouth-watering Masala Dosa.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://images.financialexpress.com/2018/06/monsoon-R.jpg\" style=\"height:440px; width:660px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The summer period is starting in March. The season is marked by the rising temperatures and moisture levels. Being a town of backwaters, it is no surprise that the rising temperature marks the humidity rise, thus making it one of the least favorable seasons for tourism.&nbsp;The temperatures vary between 25 degrees Celsius to 37 degrees Celsius with occasional showers towards the end of the season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alleppey receives heavy rainfall during monsoons which could affect your travel plans especially if you are looking for a lot of activities. The Monsoon season begins from the first week of June and stretches up to the last week of September. But this might just be the perfect place to be for a romantic vacation.&nbsp;The most important tourist activity of the region, a houseboat ride, along with other activities are occasionally hampered due to the heavy rainfall. This season also offers discounts and great deals offered by hotels looking to fill up their empty rooms.&nbsp;However, this season is the best time for any tourist looking forward to cutting costs on accommodation&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The best time to visit the &#39;Venice of the East&#39; is during winters when the weather is pleasant and calm, with temperatures ranging between 20 degrees Celsius to 32 degrees Celsius. The boat rides and other tourist activities are in full swing during this period. Winters in this tropical paradise are not too chilly and a light jacket would suffice even at night.&nbsp;</p>', '<h2><strong>Enchanting Beaches </strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.pinimg.com/originals/f4/62/99/f462992e52e6bda47cc0d45ed0ac641b.jpg\" style=\"height:440px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Alleppey is a place that is blended with Backwater and beach, a lot of explored and unexplored beaches in Alleppey. If you have had enough of the obvious Alleppey beach, then consider exploring the others. There are quite a few not so crowded beaches in this beach town such as the Thumpoly beach and the Pozhiyoram beach. And Marari beach, Aruthungal beach with a panoramic view of Aruthungal church also famous.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2><strong><strong>Backwater Cruise</strong></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.kumarakom.com/files/slides/34468456.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>We can have a different type of backwater cruise package in Alleppey. It is, hands down, one of the prominent things to do here. Sail through the canals observing local life, enjoying the splendid view of paddies and marveling at isolated islands.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2><strong><strong>Snake Boat Race</strong></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://betablog.veenaworld.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/kerala-snake-boat-race-feature-image.jpg\" style=\"height:440px; width:800px\" /></strong></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The snake boat race gets its name from the shape of the boat used for racing. It is a long canoe-style boat that is used by the people in Kerala to participate in the racing competitions in the backwaters. Head to Alleppey, in August, for the famed snake boat race which is held every year in the Punnamada Lake, near the beach town. The snake boat race traditionally started as a form of combat between the various fiefdoms that used to rule the area earlier. This is one of the best and most memorable experiences to gather in Alleppey.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;This is a historical war boat of Kerala which is about 100-120 ft long and can hold up about 100 rowers. Snake boat is the pride of the villages in this region and every village has snake boats of its own.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2><strong><strong>Rejuvenate through Ayurvedic Spa</strong></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://d16l0urwriu290.cloudfront.net/images/resizeimage/media/wellness_center/2449/packages/3147/750x562/85/WC_15500755131837259149.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:600px\" /></strong></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ayurvedic spa helps to refresh your mind and body, There&rsquo;s nothing like a good rejuvenating spa during a vacation. And when such luxury is clubbed with good health and healing, you know that you have got the best deal.&nbsp;In Kerala, a state which is famous for Ayurveda, you don&rsquo;t have to try too hard for such an experience.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2><strong><strong>Fishing</strong></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://lakepalaceresort.com/blog/img/blog/Fishing.jpg\" style=\"height:424px; width:800px\" /></strong></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Alleppey is heavily connected by the backwaters. Besides that, there is a profusion of lakes. Just buy or hire a fishing rod and enjoy a laid back day that will most certainly end with a barbeque party by night.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h2>', 'alappuzha', '2020-04-29 16:12:24', '2020-04-29 20:12:24'),
(28, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Kanyakumari', 'image/destinations/kanyakumari1925013003.jpeg', 'October', 'March', 1, 3, 'Trivandrum (100 km)', 'Kanyakumari (1 km)', 'Kanyakumari lies at the southernmost tip of the Indian peninsula, where the Indian Ocean, Arabian Sea, and Bay of Bengal confluence. Kanniyakumari district is the smallest district in Tamil Nadu. It is famous for its beautiful views of sunrise and sunset over the waters. The multicolored sand is a unique feature of the beach here. \r\n Kanyakumari was once referred to as the Alexandria of the east. This place has been a great center for art, culture, civilization, and pilgrimage for years. It was also a famous center for commerce and trade. During the early part of the eighth century AD, Islam entered the southern part of India through the sea route with traders and missionaries.', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://kerala.com/kanyakumari/wp-content/gallery/kanyakumarigallery/1.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:597px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<h3><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://kerala.com/kanyakumari/wp-content/gallery/kanyakumarigallery/5.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:597px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Visit historical monuments in Kanyakumari</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Great historical monuments in Kanyakumari exhibit a rich blend of ethnic and modern architectural styles. They are the heritage properties of India and are eloquently bedecked with intricate carvings. Kanyakumari lies in the Southern tip of India and is the point of confluence of the two great seas; the Arabian Sea and the Bay of Bengal with the grand Indian Ocean.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Kanyakumari has well-established Road networks, Rail, and Air routes that you can take to reach the entire state. All the major destinations are interconnected with perfect roadways. The remarkable thing is, the state also has some water routes available too!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.revv.co.in/blogs/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/best-road-trip-from-chennai.png\" style=\"height:448px; width:796px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>By Air:&nbsp;</strong>The closest airport is at Trivandrum (100 km). It is directly connected with Bangalore, Mumbai, Cochin, Delhi, Goa, and Chennai by regular flights. International flights also operate regularly.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>By Rail</strong>: The Kanyakumari Railway Station is situated in the city center. Kanyakumari is connected to Thiruvananthapuram, Delhi, and Mumbai by the broad-gauge railway network. Tirunelvelli (80 km) is the other nearest railway junction and can be reached by road via Nagarkoil (19 km)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>By Road:</strong>&nbsp;Kanyakumari is well connected by road to Thekkady (358 km), Kodaikanal (362 km), Palani (370 km), Ootacamund (576 km), Cochin (309 km) Trivandrum (86 km), Nagarkoil (19 km), Tirunelvelli (91 km), Tiruchendur (89 km), Tuticorin (129 km), Rameshwaram (300 km), Courtallam (130 km), Madurai (242 km), and Coimbatore (478 km). We would provide you all India tourist permit vehicles for the local transportations and also for the intercity drives too.</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.kanyakumaritourism.co.in/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Kanyakumari-Shell-Shops.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:851px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kanyakumari is well known for its shell art industry. Seashells, painted0 shells, handicrafts made from shells, and things decorated with seashells dominate the souvenir selection at Kanyakumari. You can even get a customized shell with your name engraved on it. Vendors line the seafront walkway with an array of colossal shells. You&#39;ll find more in the shops on atmospheric Sannathi Street (the main market area) leading to Kumari Amman Temple. This market has shops selling lovely woven handloom saris as well. They&#39;re sold everywhere and collectors will love them!</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://static.toiimg.com/photo/58022393/.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:672px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Kanyakumari is not only famous for its tourism but also its food items. These are some of the mouthwatering and the lip-smacking list of food items. Banana Chips, Made from under-ripe bananas, the banana chips are a tasty snack to try when at Kanyakumari. Kothu (Minced Parotta) A popular delicacy of Tamil Nadu, the Kothu Parotta is a unique version of the plain old parotta. This dish is made using parotta, egg, meat, and Salna (a spicy sauce). Pazha sarbath, the best way to beat the summer heat, the Pazha sarbath is easily available at the roadside shops at Kanyakumari. This sarbath or juice is made from a mixture of fruits like Banana, Apple, Pineapple, Grapes, Pomegranates, and so on. These fruits are nicely minced and are mixed with ice as well as sarbath.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://kerala.com/kanyakumari/wp-content/gallery/kanyakumarigallery/3.jpg\" style=\"height:440px; width:587px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The place experiences a moderate climate throughout the year. However, the best time to visit Kanyakumari is in winter, from October to March. The weather is cool and pleasant, with the warm sun to give a company, making it an ideal time for sightseeing and outdoor activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since it is a coastal town, summers are cooler than most places, but humidity is high, making it difficult to roam around the place during all hours of the day. Early mornings and evenings are cooler. Kanyakumari gets a heavy monsoon and it makes the town even more beautiful.</p>', '<h2><strong>Visit the Thiruvalluvar Statue</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://kerala.com/kanyakumari/wp-content/gallery/kanyakumarigallery/8.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:597px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A towering statue of the great Tamil poet and philosopher Thiruvalluvar stands on a smaller neighboring rock, just off the coast of Kanyakumari. Its one of the prominent attractions in Kanyakumari, The foundation stone was laid in 1979 and the work was completed 20 years later, in 1999. Ferries to Vivekananda Rock Memorial stop at the Thiruvalluvar statue afterward if the tide permits. It&#39;s possible to go inside the base of the statue and climb the stairs up to its feet for a superb view, as long as it&#39;s not closed for periodic maintenance.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Visit Vivekananda Rock Memorial</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/RockMemorial.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:597px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The great revered Indian poet and Hindu philosopher Swami Vivekananda visited Kanyakumari in 1892, towards the end of an extensive trip across India as a wandering monk. His transformation into an influential leader and reformer is attributed to the three days he spent meditating on a large offshore rock, where Goddess Kanya Kumari is said to have carried out part of her penance by standing on one foot. (According to ancient Hindu texts, the&nbsp;<em>Puranas</em>, the rock was blessed by the touch of her foot). A memorial was built on the rock in 1970 to honor Swami Vivekananda. It consists of a pavilion with a life-size bronze statue of the Swami, a hall with information about his life, and a meditation area. There&#39;s also a carving of the Goddess&#39;s foot on the rock. To get there, take a 15-minute ferry ride from Kanyakumari beach. The service operates from 8 a.m. to 4.30 p.m. (or 7 a.m. to 5.30 p.m. depending on the time of year). Buy a premium ticket, costing 169 rupees, to avoid waiting in the ticket line for up to two hours during peak times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Bathe at Triveni Sangam</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.pinimg.com/originals/36/70/72/3670720292c31770943e041ffe45939f.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:707px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where the oceans merge, known as Triveni Sangam, is considered to be powerful and sacred. A dip in the water will wash away all sins and provide liberation from the cycle of rebirth. Even if you don&#39;t want to participate in the ritual, it&#39;s still worth spending some time at this unique place and contemplating its essence. Depending on the tide and weather, you may even be able to distinguish the oceans from each other, based on variations in their shades of blue.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Watch the Sunrise and Sunset</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://kanyakumaritourism.in/images//tourist-places/sunset-point-kanyakumari/sunset-point-kanyakumari-india-tourism-history.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:840px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is one of the prominent attractions in Kanyakumari Priceless sunrises and sunsets, on Kanyakumari&#39;s liquid horizon, are among the finest in India. Sunrise, alongside the Thiruvalluvar statue, is arguably the most majestic of the two. However, sunsets are particularly special on full moon nights, when the moon rises from the sea opposite the setting sun at about the same time. The following morning, it&#39;s possible to see the sun rising and the full moon setting together. Sunsets into the sea are best viewed from the beach during the period December to February (and are only really visible from there between mid-October and mid-March). Be prepared to join the crowd! It swells on Chitra Purnima (the auspicious full moon in April). For an alternative, year-round, panoramic view of the sunrise and sunset head to Murugan Kundram on a nearby hill.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Goddess Kanya Kumari temple</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-s/05/34/1d/8c/hotel-sri-maniya.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:598px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Temple is also known as Arulmigu Bhagavathy Amman Temple is dedicated to Goddess Kanya Kumari. The town&#39;s 3,000-year-old Kumari Amman Temple, who is worshiped as a great protector after destroying mighty demon king Banasura. This great temple sits by the sea close to Triveni Sangam and has a stunning black stone idol of the goddess. The standout feature is her sparkling stunning bejeweled nose ring. Non-Hindus can also enter the temple. It&#39;s open from 4.30 a.m. to noon, and 4 p.m. to 8 p.m. Do note that photography is prohibited, bags must be left outside, and men must remove their shirts before going into the inner sanctum (where the idol is). You can buy a ticket for 20 rupees to avoid lining up. The&nbsp;Navaratri festival in October&nbsp;is a major festival at the temple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Enjoy Poovar &amp; Pathmanabhapuram palace</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.keralatourism.org/images/service-providers/photos/property-3322-profile-7685-20180720180105.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:796px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the way from Trivandrum, we can stop and enjoy some valuable spots.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Poovar island and beach is one of the enchanting gems located on a small island with the same name at a distance of 27 km from Thiruvananthapuram. This comparatively unexplored beach is blended between the Arabian Sea and Neyyar river. The golden sand island, coconut palms, cruising, houseboats, and formation of backwaters make Poovar Beach worth the trip.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Padmanabhapuram Palace is located in Padmanabhapuram, Kanyakumari District, its a Travancore era palace, Travancore royal dynasty. The palace is maintained by Kerala government even its located in Tamilnadu, This wooden palace of the 16th century is a fine specimen of Kerala&#39;s most beautiful style of architecture. The interiors in the palace are unique and best in class which is made of pure sculptured decor and rosewood carvings. The Palace though surrounded by the State of Tamil Nadu is still part of Kerala and the land and Palace belong to the Government of Kerala. The palace is open to visiting on all days except Mondays between 9 AM to 5 PM. One can easily travel by cab or taxi as it is very near to Trivandrum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'kanyakumari', '2020-04-28 05:57:45', '2020-04-28 09:57:45'),
(29, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Kodaikanal', 'image/destinations/kodaikanal536161973.jpeg', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Madurai (120 km)', 'Kodaikanal Road (80km )', NULL, '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://pix10.agoda.net/hotelImages/338376/-1/ab67f0821c0f583932d89782ddcf123b.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kodaikanal is a celebrated hill station of Tamil Nadu. It is South India&lsquo;s famous hill station famous for its breathtaking views, home-made chocolates, fleshy carrots and plums, high waterfalls, delicious baked goodies, and the world-famous magic mushroom, Its forested slopes, huge rocks, lovely waterfalls, and a beautiful lake are its jewels. Its sheer natural beauty earned it the title &#39;Princess of hill stations&#39;. It has been a famous tourist destination for ages. This hill station stands 7200 feet above sea level and situated in the upper Palani Hills of the western ghats near Madurai in Tamil Nadu. Honeymooners from across the country come to Kodaikanal to spend the most precious phase of their life. It is quite popular with newlyweds.</p>', '<h3><strong>Go biking in Kodaikanal</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://skoda-wlc.s3.amazonaws.com/2/2015/12/opener130-768x283.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Even though the town can be explored on foot or in your own vehicle, biking around town is a unique experience you must savor. Plenty of health aficionados and adventure lovers who visit here, rent bikes and ride around the hill station, stopping at little cafes and bakeries, and generally having a good time on their bikes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Take a night safari</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/proxy/Nvmimhv20nJ9L5J3h95yoWP747sa1NCwpu-FS2-Tb3btV4sgSSNwkGc2obsxp4bh2UjhFJDjvk9kIr4ZLEQ3nQ-w3SGu0SyWDm0yISpYRjPdKgrEPRWMKPOJG5s\" style=\"height:480px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are plenty of organizers that offer night safaris in Kodaikanal. These are set in the plantations and forests that look and feel vividly different during the night safari. Night views of lakes, Mango Temple, and Palani Hills are thrilling and surreal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Rejuvenate with Yoga</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://content.jdmagicbox.com/def_content/yoga_classes/default-yoga-classes-4.jpg\" style=\"height:450px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Visit Karuna Farm in Kodaikanal. You can engage in cleansing and meditation with the help of experts at this ecological farm which offers yoga, meditation, and meditative art class.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Kodaikanal has well-established Road networks, Rail, and Air routes that you can take to reach the entire state. All the major destinations are interconnected with perfect roadways. The remarkable thing is, the state also has some water routes available too!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.oyorooms.com/travel-guide/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Evergreen-forests-of-Kodaikanal.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>By Air:&nbsp;</strong>The closest airport is at &nbsp;Madurai is 120 km.The other airport like &nbsp;Coimbatore 170 km&nbsp;and Trichy 195 km. It is directly connected with Bangalore, Mumbai, Cochin, Delhi, Goa, and Chennai by regular flights. International flights also operate regularly.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>By Rail</strong>: Kodaikanal is a hill station so that Kodai is not well connected with rail and there is no nearby&nbsp;railway station available in Kodaikanal town, but there is also a possibility for who loves the train travel. The nearest railway station is&nbsp;Kodaikanal&nbsp;Road (80km&nbsp;from&nbsp;Kodaikanal&nbsp;observatory). The train comes here late in the evening, so you&nbsp;don&rsquo;t have any other option but to take a cab back.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>By Road: </strong>Kodaikanal is vastly linked by road with major prominent cities, including Trichy (198 km), Bangalore (460 km), Chennai (530 km),&nbsp;Ooty&nbsp;(255 km), and Kumili (160 km). From Madurai (120 km), it takes less than four hours to reach Kodaikanal via NH 49. Depending upon their budget and requirement, travelers can choose from pocket-friendly state government buses or private luxury buses available from these cities.</li>\r\n</ul>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.treebo.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Danish-Display.jpg\" style=\"height:438px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Find homemade chocolates, marshmallows, and cheese in the bakeries &ndash; awesome all the way! The street-side small stores will amaze you with an immense array of flowers, vegetables, handmade articles, hot snacks, children&#39;s toys, medicinal herbs, oils, and almost every useful thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;In Kodaikanal, however, you&rsquo;ll find scores of shops selling great-smelling oils and balms. Citronella oil, neem oil, pain balms, and wintergreen oil (red and white versions) can also be purchased at very modest fares. The Eucalyptus trees are grown in large numbers in this region, and hence, it is very easy to find the medicinal oil extracted from this tree The next best thing your money could buy in the town is chocolates!. &nbsp;</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://img.traveltriangle.com/blog/wp-content/tr:w-700,h-400/uploads/2019/06/Dosa-Bar1.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are a foodie, you would enjoy every bit of Kodai, do not stop eating crisp dosas and piping hot idlis with coconut chutney. But what happens when you&rsquo;re done to death (unimaginable, but okay) with it? Cloud Street comes to your rescue! Satiate your cravings for Italian food here with an authentic wood-fired pizza or oven-baked pasta, or gorge on some Lebanese goodness like hummus and falafel. Have a sweet tooth to calm? Try the homemade cakes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The major hotels are Hilltop hotel which near to the lake, Hilltop has a variety of menu for South Indians !!. It has both vegetarian and nonvegetarian hotels separately. Another one is the Hotel Astoria<br />\r\nThis hotel is just near the bus stand of Kodaikanal !! You must not miss this hotel although it&#39;s a vegetarian hotel.</p>', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://static2.tripoto.com/media/filter/tst/img/109540/TripDocument/1457072853_1457072849_378359.png\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The best time to visit Kodaikanal is from April to June or August to September, So, this is the finest climate to visit Kodaikanal. Generally, Temperatures will be in the region of a comfortable 20&deg;C to a bracing 10&deg;C.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are a person who would be interested in attending flower-shows, dog shows, boat- races, then &ldquo;may&rdquo; month would be the best time for you to visit Kodaikanal. During this season, Kodaikanal will be a little crowded than usual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oct to March is likely too cold with some rains as well but it is still a charming place for a quiet break at that time of the year. If you can take the cold we would recommend this time when things are very quiet. Towards the end of March, the weather is starting to heat up and the crowd starts to come in again.</p>', '<h2><strong>Enjoy boating in Kodai lake </strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://static.toiimg.com/photo/58640316/.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Kodaikanal Lake is the prominent attraction in Kodaikanal and one of the most popular tourist destinations of Tamil Nadu. This star-shaped artificial lake is located at an elevation of 2285 meters above sea level. Kodai Lake was constructed way back in 1863 by Sir Vere Hentry Levinge, the collector of Madurai. He moved to Kodaikanal after his retirement and decided to build this lake on abandoned marshy land. Currently, activities like cycling, fishing, and boating can be done here.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Have a romantic walk in&nbsp; Coaker&#39;s Walk</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ngtraveller.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/7.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s the best romantic spot in Kodaikanal if you miss the place you will feel the holiday in Kodaikanal is incomplete. A man-made walking plaza, Coaker&#39;s Walk was created by Lt Coaker in 1872. Today it is one of the best popular places to visit in Kodaikanal. Take a stroll in the afternoon with your partner, or simply gaze at the verdant green valleys-a short trip to the Coaker&#39;s Walk will fill you with lifetime memories.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Enjoy the Pine Forest</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/zo2WgUD.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The forest is an ideal place to go for long walks, admiring its unique beauty and enjoying its peaceful atmosphere. The Pine Forest of Kodaikanal was cultivated by one Mr. Bryant about a century ago and today, it happens to be one of the most visited places in the hill station. One of the most popular things to do at Pine Forest is photography. The Pine Forest attracts a multitude of tourists from all over. Nature enthusiasts are sure to love this place. One can also have an exciting camping experience here after getting permission from the local authorities</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Guna Caves (Devil&rsquo;s Kitchen) </strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-IFVqIZxjUGE/Vrmp1qukziI/AAAAAAAAZ88/OPTebQ8hWnk/s1600/Kodaikanal_GunaCaves%2B%252815%2529.JPG\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Guna caves found their place between three mammoth pillar-shaped rocks. It&#39;s an interesting place to visit with mythological stories situated in the Guna caves that the Pandavas lived and cooked their foods here. It is a very steep set of caves to get in, which increases the risk factor and hence the adventure in exploring the place. Because of its fatal history, visitors are not allowed to enter the cave. Though, it is still a hot spot for clicking pictures. The Guna Caves were discovered in the year 1821<br />\r\nThe discovery of this cave was made by the British officer B.S. Ward. These caves are truly marvelous in the true sense of the term. It is said that the place of Guna caves was found with some hidden treasures just like many other places near Kodaikanal. The hidden treasures were greedily enjoyed by the Britishers. The caves were lost in the rush of the cities. It is quite an astonishing fact that the caves got their new name Guna as of a famous Indian (Tamil) movie which was shot there around the early 90s.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Pillar Rocks</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dyfda37ceab0a.cloudfront.net/template/upload/news/7-Best-Places-at-Kodaikanal-in-India-for-Travelers-2019-2.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kodaikanal&rsquo;s one of the most famous&nbsp;attractions, these three mammoth rock pillars stand shoulder-to-shoulder, looming 400-ft-high in the sky. Pillar Rocks are three vertical granite boulders, standing shoulder to shoulder amidst untouched packets of dense rainforests. It is better to travel here in the summer season to have a clear view of the rock formations. Unique and visually stunning. this place is ideal for a hangout with your friends or an escape with your loved ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Dolphin Nouse</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-WezY4tgE4Ak/VrjmkkdCcmI/AAAAAAAAZog/KztLQy3PZ6o/s1600/side-view-of-dolphins-nose.jpg\" style=\"height:448px; width:800px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dolphin&#39;s Nose, laying at an altitude of 6,600 ft, is located at a distance of 8 km from the heart of the city of Kodaikanal. The place is one of the major attractions of the destination as it offers a bird&#39;s eye view of the beautiful landscape of the hilly region. Orange juice vendors along the trail offer a welcome rest stop. Endowed with the scenic beauty, the best time to make a visit to Dolphin&#39;s Nose extends from the month of October to March. It is an undisturbed area 1 kilometer down a very steep rocky trail beginning soon after Pambar Bridge. Beautiful views of steep rocky escarpments rising from the plains can be seen.</p>', 'kodaikanal', '2020-04-30 17:17:21', '2020-04-30 21:17:21');
